==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: octamer
<hw>oc"ta*mer</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧k"t⟦ucr⟧*m⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Octa-</ets> + Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part.]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A molecule composed of eight monomer units bound
to each other, usually in a linear array; <as>as, an <ex>octamer</ex>
formed from eight nucleotides is called an
octanucleotide</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>An example of an octapeptide might be represented using the
standard abbreviations for the component amino acids, e.g.:
met-ala-ser-glu-lys-ala-val-gly⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
An octanucleotide might be represented using the standard single-letter
abbreviations for the component mononucleotides, e.g.:
ATGCATGC.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>octamerous</ent>⟦br⟧
